  "prompt": "What is the status of net neutrality in all countries?",
  "response": "As of my last update in October 2023, net neutrality laws and regulations vary significantly across countries. Here\u2019s a general overview of the status of net neutrality in various regions:\n\n### United States\n- **Status**: Repealed\n- **Details**: The Federal Communications Commission (FCC) voted to repeal net neutrality regulations in 2017 under the Trump Administration. This decision has led to ongoing debates and attempts to reinstate such regulations at both the federal and state levels.\n\n### European Union\n- **Status**: Enforced\n- **Details**: The EU has robust net neutrality rules established under the GNI Regulation that came into effect in 2016. These rules prohibit internet service providers (ISPs) from blocking or throttling internet traffic and ensure that all data is treated equally.\n\n### Canada\n- **Status**: Enforced\n- **Details**: The Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission (CRTC) has implemented net neutrality rules that prohibit ISPs from engaging in discriminatory practices regarding internet traffic.\n\n### India\n- **Status**: Enforced\n- **Details**: The Telecom Regulatory Authority of India (TRAI) imposed strict net neutrality rules in 2018, preventing ISPs from blocking or throttling content and ensuring equal treatment of all internet traffic.\n\n### Australia\n- **Status**: Not explicitly enforced\n- **Details**: There are no formal net neutrality laws, but discussions and advocacy for such regulations continue. The Australian Communications and Media Authority oversees compliance with fair trading laws that may touch on net neutrality issues.\n\n### Brazil\n- **Status**: Enforced\n- **Details**: Brazil's Marco Civil da Internet law, enacted in 2014, mandates net neutrality and prohibits ISPs from prioritizing certain types of internet traffic over others.\n\n### Other Regions\n- In several countries throughout Africa, Asia, and Latin America, net neutrality has either been partially established or is under discussion, with varying degrees of enforcement. Some countries like Chile have implemented net neutrality laws, while others are still evolving their regulations.\n\n### Summary\nThe global landscape of net neutrality is diverse, with some countries firmly supporting it and others allowing for more variability in internet management. Ongoing discussions and legal challenges in various regions continue to shape the future of net neutrality. It's important to check for the most current developments, as this status can change with new regulations and political shifts.",
